Example data sets

Intro

This is a script reading in a number of classic network data sets that we will use to investigate various random graph models. Most of this data is uploaded in raw text files on https://github.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/tree/main/data. If you want to download a data set outside of this vignette, navigate to the file you want, then press the raw button. This will open the file in a new tab. Alternatively, right-click on the the raw button and chose save link as.

Download data from GitHub

Files on GitHub repos

Make sure that you have loaded the required libraries.

library("sna")
library("network")

Tasks

For each network we read in, we will format it and plot it, as well as calculating some summary statistics for the network.

Non-directed networks

Padgetts business network

This is an \(n=16\) subset of the classic Padgett and Ansell (1993) Florentine families business network

padgettbus <- as.matrix(read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/main/data/PADGB.txt"))
gden(padgettbus)# using sna to calculate density of an adjacency matrix
## [1] 0.125
padgbus.net <- as.network( padgettbus , directed=FALSE)# translate the matrix to a network object
padgbus.net
##  Network attributes:
##   vertices = 16 
##   directed = FALSE 
##   hyper = FALSE 
##   loops = FALSE 
##   multiple = FALSE 
##   bipartite = FALSE 
##   total edges= 15 
##     missing edges= 0 
##     non-missing edges= 15 
## 
##  Vertex attribute names: 
##     vertex.names 
## 
## No edge attributes

The network is undirected and has a density of 12.5%

plot( padgbus.net )

Red Highland Tribes

A classic training data set, originally collected by Read (1954), is that of \(n=16\) tribes of the GahukuGama alliance structure of the Eastern Central Highlands of New Guinea and their positive and negative ties (Hage and Harary 1983).

tribesNeg <-tribes.all[17:32,]# the bottomw 16 lines are the negative ties

Bank wiring room

Coming out of an extensive study by Mayo, Roethlisberger, and Dickson (1939), this dataset maps the ineractions among \(n=14\) emplyoyes The interaction categories include: RDGAM, participation in horseplay; RDCON, participation in arguments about open windows; RDPOS, friendship; RDNEG, antagonistic (negative) behavior; RDHLP, helping others with work; and RDJOB, the number of times workers traded job assignments.

wiring  <- as.matrix(read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/main/data/bankwiring.txt"))

RDGAM <- wiring[1:14,]# RDGAM symmetric, binary, participation in horseplay
RDCON <- wiring[15:(2*14),]# RDCON symmetric, binary, participation in arguments about open windows
RDPOS <- wiring[(2*14+1):(3*14),]# RDPOS symmetric, binary,  friendship
RDNEG <- wiring[(3*14+1):(4*14),]# RDNEG symmetric, binary, antagonistic (negative) behavior

gden(RDGAM)# using sna to calculate density of an adjacency matrix
## [1] 0.3076923
gden(RDCON)
## [1] 0.2087912
gden(RDPOS)
## [1] 0.1428571
gden(RDNEG)
## [1] 0.2087912
RDGAM.net <- as.network( RDGAM , directed=FALSE)# translate the matrix to a network object
RDGAM.net

Zacharys karate club

A network of \(n=34\) members of a karate club (made famous as the testbed for community detection and blockmodelling algorithms) from the work of Zachary (1977)

Zachary  <- as.matrix(read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/main/data/zachary.txt"))

ZacharyBinary <- Zachary[1:34,]# symmetric, binary, positive

Sagemans Terrorist data

Webster

This is a symmetrised an binary version of a data set collected by Cinthia Webster (Webster 1993, webster95context) on both work ties and social ties from \(n=24\) members of a small accounting firm (the original ties were called REPORTED_SOCIAL).

Webster  <- as.matrix(read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/main/data/WebsterSymmetricSocial.txt"))
# symmetrised version of REPORTED_SOCIAL non-symmetric, valued

gden(Webster)
## [1] 0.4384058
Webster.net <- as.network( Webster , directed=FALSE)# translate the matrix to a network object
Webster.net
##  Network attributes:
##   vertices = 24

##   hyper = FALSE 
##   loops = FALSE 
##   multiple = FALSE 
##   bipartite = FALSE 
##   total edges= 121 
##     missing edges= 0 
##     non-missing edges= 121 
## 
##  Vertex attribute names: 
##     vertex.names 
## 
## No edge attributes

Load some attributes as well

WebsterAtt   <- read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/main/data/WebsterAtt.txt")
# WebsterAtt.txt: One 242 matrix: 
# Column 1, sex (1 = male. 2 = female
# Column 2, job (1 = Partner, 2 = Manager, 3 = Accountant, 4 = Staff member
head(WebsterAtt)
##   V1 V2
## 1  1  1
## 2  1  1
## 3  1  1
## 4  2  3
## 5  2  3
## 6  1  2
vertex.sides <- matrix(50,dim(WebsterAtt)[1],1)# to use for plotting
vertex.sides[WebsterAtt[,1]==2] <- 4# females will be square

Plot

plot( Webster.net, vertex.col=WebsterAtt[,2] , vertex.sides =vertex.sides)

EIES

The Electronic Information Exchange System (EIES) data were collected by Linton Freeman. The codes 1-4 have the following meanings. 1. do not know the other 2. heard about the other, did not meet him/her 3. have met the other 4. friend.

We will only use friend.

EIES1  <- as.matrix(read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/main/data/EIES.1.txt",header=FALSE))
EIES2  <- as.matrix(read.table("https://raw.githubusercontent.com/johankoskinen/CHDH-SNA/main/data/EIES.2.txt",header=FALSE))

EIES1[EIES1<4] <- 0
EIES1[EIES1>0] <-1
EIES2[EIES2<4] <- 0
EIES2[EIES2>0] <-1
EIES1.net <- as.network( EIES1 ,directed=FALSE)
EIES2.net <-  as.network( EIES2 ,directed=FALSE) 
EIES1.net
##  Network attributes:
##   vertices = 32 
##   directed = FALSE 
##   hyper = FALSE 
##   loops = FALSE 
##   multiple = FALSE 
##   bipartite = FALSE 
##   total edges= 27 
##     missing edges= 0 
##     non-missing edges= 27 
## 
##  Vertex attribute names: 
##     vertex.names 
## 
## No edge attributes
EIES2.net
##  Network attributes:

Variables are the Number of citations and Discipline: 1 = sociology, 2 = anthropology, 3 = mathematics / statistics, 4 = psychology.

head(EIESATT)

plot( EIES2.net, vertex.col = EIESATT[,2] , coord=coord )
